Article.find_or_create_by!(slug: "internal-linking-frameworks") do |a|
  a.title = "SEO: 5 Frameworks for Internal Linking"
  a.excerpt = "SEO is an amazing organic channel to grow your startup. Learn 5 key frameworks to improve internal linking on your website & ace rankings on Google."
  a.content = "Our startups get 1.5M monthly SEO traffic!\n\nWe write quality content & do amazing optimisations. But that's not it.\n\nWe also have a solid marketing strategy for link building.\n\nToday I am sharing 5 frameworks we use for internal linking 🧵\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nOur startups get 1.5M monthly SEO traffic!\n\nWe write quality content & do amazing optimisations. But that's not it.\n\nWe also have a solid marketing strategy for link building.\n\nToday I am sharing 5 frameworks we use for internal linking 🧵\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nInternal links help:\n\n1) Pass on authority between pages\n\n2) Google to crawl your website easily\n\nPlus you have full control on your internal link structure.\n\nThe frameworks below will help you lay out an internal linking structure for your website 👇\n\n(2/2)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\n– Helps to identify sub-folders or pages for which you need to build authority\n\nHow?\n\n– All pages are organised into well thought out sub-folders\n– Every time a new page is to be created, you know exactly which sub-folder it belongs to\n\n(2/4)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nEg. your product pages can be at\n\nHomepage → Category → Sub-category → Product.\n\nBut your URL can just be /product/<<product-name>>.\n\nThis helps you avoid long URLs like /<<category>>/<<sub-category>>/<<product-name>>.\n\nCase Study:https://t.co/R5mqAqbNpA\n\n(4/4)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nWhy?\n\n– Easy interlinking between pages under the same topic\n\n– SEO juice can flow across pages ie if one page gets good authority, the goodness gets passed onto other pages as well\n\n– Helps you get “topical authority” from Google\n\n(2/3)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\n3/ Framework 3: Internal Linking Engine\n\nAdding internal links without a proper structure or a set of rules will have 0 to little impact.\n\nSo it’s important you establish guidelines for internal linking that are followed for every page on the website.\n\n(1/3)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nHow?\n\n– Set specific rules along with min/max threshold on number of links\n\n– Sample engine\n— Min 2 internal links from pages under the same topic\n— Min 3 internal links from other parts of the website\n\n(3/3)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nWhy?\n\n– Other pages on your website get a boost through links from your \"power pages\"\n\n– It serves as a powerful hack when you want to promote certain pages or sections\n\n(2/5)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nIdentifying power pages:\n\n– Tools like Ahrefs or SEMRush show you page authority & number of domains linking to a page\n\n– Sort all pages on your website by page authority. Top pages in the list are your power pages\n\n(4/5)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\n5/ Framework 5: Audit Engine\n\nA key element of any internal linking strategy is to periodically check for and rectify errors.\n\nRegular SEO audits will give you a good list of points to work on.\n\n(1/3)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022\n\nHow?\n\n– Use any SEO tool to do a site audit\n\n– Check for these issues\n—  Orphan page\n— Broken internal links\n— Internal links to redirected pages\n\n– Set a frequency to do these audits & clean errors. Eg. every 2 months.\n\n(3/3)\n\n— Hrishikesh Pardeshi (@hrishiptweets) March 31, 2022"
  a.category = cat
  a.published = true
  a.published_at = DateTime.parse("2022-11-01T11:02:00")
end

